object.script:
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function pgt(k) return property.getText(k) end
function pgn(k) return property.getNumber(k) end
title=pgt("Title") fmt=pgt("Format string") elwidth=pgn("Element width") elheight=pgn("Element height") gridw=pgn("Grid width") gridh=pgn("Grid height") warnmin=pgn("Warn min") warnmax=pgn("Warn max") ct=gridw*gridh
buf={}
colw=5 rowh=6
posy=0 layoutw=colw*((elwidth+1)*gridw-1)
if #title then posy=posy+rowh*2 end
function onTick() local i for i=1,ct do buf[i]=gn(i) end end
safecol={0,255,0} dangcol={255,0,0}
function scale_color(x,c) return { c[1]*x, c[2]*x,c[3]*x } end
-- updates c to avoid an allocation function add_colors(c,d) c[1]=d[1]+c[1] c[2]=d[2]+c[2] c[3]=d[3]+c[3] return c end
function clamp(v,mn,mx) return math.max(math.min(v,mx),mn) end
function draw_cell(n) local gridx,gridy,gradfac,val,color,color2
val=buf[n] gridx=((n-1)%gridw)+1 gridy=math.floor((n-1)/gridw)+1 gradfac=clamp((val-warnmin)/(warnmax-warnmin),0,1) color=scale_color(1-gradfac,safecol) color2=scale_color(gradfac,dangcol) add_colors(color,color2) screen.setColor(color[1], color[2], color[3])
local x=(elwidth+1)*colw*(gridx-1) local y=(gridy-1)*rowh*elheight screen.drawText(x,posy+y,string.format(fmt, val)) end
function onDraw() local n=1 w=screen.getWidth() if #title then screen.setColor(0,255,0) screen.drawText((layoutw-#title*colw)/2,0,title) end
for n=1,ct do draw_cell(n) end end

object.script:
inf=1/0
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function sn(n,v) output.setNumber(n,v) end
function gb(n) return input.getBool(n) end
function sb(n,v) output.setBool(n,v) end
-- -- Ordnance telemetry protocol (output) -- We overlay the contact age field since I never found it to work anyway -- These fields are optional and the booleans specify whether the piece of ordnance provides them -- Boolean 9: Lock ordinal: If true, Numeric 4 contains the contact ordinal of the locked or targeted contact -- Boolean 10: FOV: If true, Number 8 contains the FOV of the weapon's sensors for drawing a targeting ring -- on the HUD -- Boolean 11 Range. Offer sensor rang on Bool 12 to draw a ring on the radar
-- Number 4: Ordinal of lock-on contact. In the case of stock missile radar heads, it's always the closest contact -- Number 8: FOV so that it can be displayed on the HUD -- Number 12: Weapon sensor/targeting range in meters -- Number 16: Reserved for ordnance type read from hardpoint and inserted later by MCU -- Number 3
-- Protocol (input) -- Numeric 1: Hardpoint #/bus address -- Boolean 1: Launch (applied also to hardpoint) -- Boolean 9: Enable the weapon's sensors (radar etc.) which should use the game's standard radar -- protocol to report contacts on the composite-out. -- Check gb(9) to see whether the pilot is scanning for a target.
function onTick()
local range=inf local nearest=0 local r local present
scan=gb(9)
if not scan then return end
for i=1,8,1 do present = gb(i) sb(i,present) if present then r=gn(i*4-3) if r < range and r > 100 then -- Assume that anything inside 100m is self-detection range=r nearest=i end end end
for i=1,32,1 do sn(i,gn(i)) end
sb(9,true) -- Notify we will report a target ordinal sb(10,true) -- Notify we will report sensor/radar FOV sb(11,true) -- Notify we will provide sensor range
sn(4,nearest) sn(8,20) -- Roughly 20 degrees sn(12,2000) -- 2km gives about a 20 degree X/Y FOV. Should match the radar head configuration. end
function onDraw() end

object.script:
-- We dedicate this MCU solely to calculating the zoom range and displaying -- that figure along with the radar ring, forwarding the zoom scale in meters range, -- and the enable-status. That way, we can chain any number -- of additional sensor unit MCUs to overdraw their contacts. You might need -- three for sonar, radar, and ordnance, or who knows what else.
function gb(n) return input.getBool(n) end
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function sn(n,v) output.setNumber(n,v) end
function sb(n,v) output.setBool(n,v) end
min_zoom=property.getNumber("Radar min zoom") zoom_count=property.getNumber("Radar zooms") zoom=1 scale=property.getNumber("radar scale")
-- Treat floats as ints for comparison function intcomp(a,b) return math.abs(a-b) < 0.5 end
function clamp(x,l,h) return math.max(math.min(h,x),l) end
scale2=1000 zoom=1 function onTick() enabled=gb(32) sb(32,enabled) if not enabled then return end -- If not enabled zoom=clamp(math.floor(zoom+gn(32)),1,zoom_count)
if intcomp(zoom,1) then scale2=min_zoom else scale2=scale*zoom/zoom_count end sn(32,scale2) end
function radius(a,b) return math.min(a,b)-1 end
function onDraw()
if not enabled then return end
w=screen.getWidth() h=screen.getHeight() cx=w/2 cy=h/2 r=radius(cx,cy)
-- Display radar ring screen.setColor(0, 255, 0) screen.drawCircle(w / 2, h / 2, r)
-- Display range distance local fmt local tmp -- Show meters if the range is less than 1km, otherwise show km if scale2<1000 then fmt="%.0fm" tmp=scale2 else fmt="%.0fkm" tmp = scale2/1000 end screen.drawTextBox(0,0, cx, cy, string.format(fmt, tmp)) end

object.script:
-- Clock rolls over here clock_roll=9999999 clock=0 sweep_enable=false
function pgn(k) return property.getNumber(k) end
function gb(n) return input.getBool(n) end
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function sb(n,v) output.setBool(n,v) end
function intcomp(x,y) return math.abs(x-y) < 0.5 end
-- How long to remember a contact. The stock radars are probably supposed to do this given that they -- provide an age field, but stuff just blinks in and out instantly.Seconds. contact_dwell=pgn("Blip dwell") dwell_ticks=contact_dwell*60 az_mult=pgn("Azimuth multiplier") az_offs=pgn("Azimuth offset") sensor_type=pgn("Sensor type") -- 1=radar,2=sonar
-- range, azimuth, elevation,timestamp,which (source) contacts={count=0,array={}} lock=0
-- Treat floats as ints for comparison function intcomp(a,b) return math.abs(a-b) < 0.5 end
-- Calculate age of given timestamp in ticks function age(t) local d=clock-t if d < 0 then return clock_roll-t+clock+1 end return d end
-- Package up the contact list in an object function fetch_contacts(obj) local i, pos local entry
-- Clean out stale contacts for i=obj.count,1,-1 do entry=obj.array[i] if age(entry[4]) > dwell_ticks then table.remove(obj.array, i) if intcomp(i,lock) then lock = 0 end if i < lock then lock = lock -1 end obj.count=obj.count-1 end end
local noo local az for i=1,8,1 do if( gb(i) ) then noo=obj.count+1 pos=i*4-3 cont={}
-- Radar if sensor_type==1 then cont[1]=gn(pos) az=gn(pos+1) cont[3]=gn(pos+2) else cont[1]=math.huge az=gn(pos) cont[3]=gn(pos+1) end cont[2]=az*az_mult+az_offs cont[4]=clock
if have_locks and intcomp(lock, i) then lock = noo end obj.array[noo]=cont obj.count=obj.count+1 end end return obj end
blip_color={pgn("Blip R"),pgn("Blip G"),pgn("Blip B")} ord_range=0 ord_t=0 function onTick() enabled = gb(32) sb(32,enabled)
clock=(clock+1)%clock_roll if not enabled then return end
sweep=gn(28) sweep_enabled=sweep_enabled or sweep ~= 0 sweep=sweep*az_mult+az_offs
have_locks=gb(9) have_range=gb(11) if have_range then ord_range=gn(12) end lock=gn(4)
fetch_contacts(contacts) scale=gn(32) end
function radius(cx, cy) return math.min(cx,cy) - 1 end
function blip(cont, sc, cx, cy,color) local r = radius(cx,cy) local d=cont[1] local d2=math.min(d,sc) local pos
-- Draw a chevron pointing to blips outside the screen -- We will use this for sonar, too, since the range is unspecified pos=ray(cx,cy,cont[2],d2*r/sc) local bright=(dwell_ticks-age(cont[4]))/dwell_ticks *.76 screen.setColor(0.24 + color[1]*bright,0.24 +color[2]*bright,0.24+color[3]*bright)
if d>sc then chevron(pos[1],pos[2],cont[2],5) else screen.drawCircleF(pos[1],pos[2], 1.25) end end raypos={0,0}
-- Calculate the endpoint of a ray based on an origin, a theta in whole circles, and a length function ray(x,y,t,l) local t2=math.pi*2*t raypos[1]=x+math.sin(t2)*l raypos[2]=y+math.cos(t2)*l return raypos end
function chevron(x,y,t,l) -- local pos=ray(x,y,t+0.375,l) local pos=ray(x,y,t+0.5,l) screen.drawLine(x,y,pos[1],pos[2]) --pos=ray(x,y,t-0.375,l) --screen.drawLine(x,y,pos[1],pos[2]) end
red={0,255,0} function draw_contacts(conts,scale,lock) local i local r,g,b b=0
for i=1,conts.count do blip(conts.array[i],scale,cx,cy,blip_color) end
if have_locks and not intcomp(lock,0) then blip(conts.array[lock],scale,cx,cy,red) end end
scale=1000 function onDraw()
if not enabled then return end w=screen.getWidth() h=screen.getHeight() cx=w/2 cy=h/2 r=radius(cx,cy) screen.setColor(0, 255, 0)
-- draw the sweep line if it's active if sweep_enabled then -- local t=math.pi*2*(sweep+.5) local pos=ray(cx,cy,sweep,r) screen.drawLine(cx,cy,pos[1],pos[2]) end

-- Clock rolls over here clock_roll=9999999 clock=0 sweep_enable=false
function pgn(k) return property.getNumber(k) end
function gb(n) return input.getBool(n) end
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function sb(n,v) output.setBool(n,v) end
function intcomp(x,y) return math.abs(x-y) < 0.5 end
-- How long to remember a contact. The stock radars are probably supposed to do this given that they -- provide an age field, but stuff just blinks in and out instantly.Seconds. contact_dwell=pgn("Blip dwell") dwell_ticks=contact_dwell*60 az_mult=pgn("Azimuth multiplier") az_offs=pgn("Azimuth offset") sensor_type=pgn("Sensor type") -- 1=radar,2=sonar
-- range, azimuth, elevation,timestamp,which (source) contacts={count=0,array={}} lock=0
-- Treat floats as ints for comparison function intcomp(a,b) return math.abs(a-b) < 0.5 end
-- Calculate age of given timestamp in ticks function age(t) local d=clock-t if d < 0 then return clock_roll-t+clock+1 end return d end
-- Package up the contact list in an object function fetch_contacts(obj) local i, pos local entry
-- Clean out stale contacts for i=obj.count,1,-1 do entry=obj.array[i] if age(entry[4]) > dwell_ticks then table.remove(obj.array, i) if intcomp(i,lock) then lock = 0 end if i < lock then lock = lock -1 end obj.count=obj.count-1 end end
local noo local az for i=1,8,1 do if( gb(i) ) then noo=obj.count+1 pos=i*4-3 cont={}
-- Radar if sensor_type==1 then cont[1]=gn(pos) az=gn(pos+1) cont[3]=gn(pos+2) else cont[1]=math.huge az=gn(pos) cont[3]=gn(pos+1) end cont[2]=az*az_mult+az_offs cont[4]=clock
if have_locks and intcomp(lock, i) then lock = noo end obj.array[noo]=cont obj.count=obj.count+1 end end return obj end
blip_color={pgn("Blip R"),pgn("Blip G"),pgn("Blip B")} ord_range=0 ord_t=0 function onTick() enabled = gb(32) sb(32,enabled)
clock=(clock+1)%clock_roll if not enabled then return end
sweep=gn(28) sweep_enabled=sweep_enabled or sweep ~= 0 sweep=sweep*az_mult+az_offs
have_locks=gb(9) have_range=gb(11) if have_range then ord_range=gn(12) end lock=gn(4)
fetch_contacts(contacts) scale=gn(32) end
function radius(cx, cy) return math.min(cx,cy) - 1 end
function blip(cont, sc, cx, cy,color) local r = radius(cx,cy) local d=cont[1] local d2=math.min(d,sc) local pos
-- Draw a chevron pointing to blips outside the screen -- We will use this for sonar, too, since the range is unspecified pos=ray(cx,cy,cont[2],d2*r/sc) local bright=(dwell_ticks-age(cont[4]))/dwell_ticks *.76 screen.setColor(0.24 + color[1]*bright,0.24 +color[2]*bright,0.24+color[3]*bright)
if d>sc then chevron(pos[1],pos[2],cont[2],5) else screen.drawCircleF(pos[1],pos[2], 1.25) end end raypos={0,0}
-- Calculate the endpoint of a ray based on an origin, a theta in whole circles, and a length function ray(x,y,t,l) local t2=math.pi*2*t raypos[1]=x+math.sin(t2)*l raypos[2]=y+math.cos(t2)*l return raypos end
function chevron(x,y,t,l) -- local pos=ray(x,y,t+0.375,l) local pos=ray(x,y,t+0.5,l) screen.drawLine(x,y,pos[1],pos[2]) --pos=ray(x,y,t-0.375,l) --screen.drawLine(x,y,pos[1],pos[2]) end
red={0,255,0} function draw_contacts(conts,scale,lock) local i local r,g,b b=0
for i=1,conts.count do blip(conts.array[i],scale,cx,cy,blip_color) end
if have_locks and not intcomp(lock,0) then blip(conts.array[lock],scale,cx,cy,red) end end
scale=1000 function onDraw()
if not enabled then return end w=screen.getWidth() h=screen.getHeight() cx=w/2 cy=h/2 r=radius(cx,cy) screen.setColor(0, 255, 0)
-- draw the sweep line if it's active if sweep_enabled then -- local t=math.pi*2*(sweep+.5) local pos=ray(cx,cy,sweep,r) screen.drawLine(cx,cy,pos[1],pos[2]) end
-- Draw the ordnance range ring if active and it offers that datum if have_range and age(ord_t) < 1 then -- ord_range=2000 screen.setColor(0,16,0) screen.drawCircle(cx,cy,ord_range*r/scale) end draw_contacts(contacts,scale,lock) end

object.script:
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function gb(n) return input.getBool(n) end
function sb(n,v) output.setBool(n,v) end
function sn(n,v) output.setNumber(n,v) end
devct=6 function devinit() local tmp={} local i
for i=1,devct do tmp[i]={level=0,cap=0,rate=0,leak=false,target=0,trim=0} end return tmp end
devs=devinit()
function clamp(x,l,h) return math.max(math.min(x,h), l) end
function prop(n) return devs[n].cap*balset/100 end
trimpair={a=0,b=0} function trim(a,b,tr) local tra,trb local deva=devs[a] local devb=devs[b] local tmp
tr=tr/2 deva.trim=deva.trim-tr devb.trim=devb.trim+tr
-- If trim produces a negative setpoint, then compensate by weighing down the other side instead tmp=deva.target+deva.trim if tmp<0 then deva.trim=deva.trim-tmp devb.trim=devb.trim+tmp end
tmp=devb.target+devb.trim if tmp<0 then devb.trim=devb.trim-tmp deva.trim=deva.trim+tmp end end
function onTick() local i,j,obj,klax,bp,bs,kp,ks
balset=gn(32) klax=false j=1 for i=1,devct do obj=devs[i] obj.level=gn(j) j=j+1 obj.cap=gn(j) j=j+1 obj.rate=gn(j) j=j+1 obj.leak=gb(i) obj.target=prop(i) obj.trim=0 klax=klax or obj.leak end
rolltrim=gn(30) pitchtrim=gn(31)
-- Bow trim(1,2,rolltrim)
-- Hull trim(3,4,rolltrim)
-- Keel trim(5,6,rolltrim)
-- Pitch trim trim(5,1,pitchtrim) trim(6,2,pitchtrim)
for i=1,devct do obj=devs[i] obj.target=obj.target+obj.trim sn(i,obj.target) end
sb(32,klax) end
function drawsub(x,y,l,h) screen.setColor(0,255,0) screen.drawCircle(x+l-h/2,y+h/2,h/2) screen.setColor(0,0,0) screen.drawRectF(x,y, l-h/2,h)
local kx=x+l*.2 screen.setColor(0,255,0) screen.drawTriangle(x,y+h/2,kx,y,kx,y+h) screen.drawRect(kx,y,l-kx-h/2,h) screen.drawLine(x+l-h/2,y,x+l-h/2,y+h) end
colw=5 rowh=6 function compartment(x,y,obj) screen.setColor(0,255,0) screen.drawText(x,y,string.format("%3.0f/%3.0f%%\n" .. "dt%+3.0fL/s\n" .. "%0.0fK/%0.0fK\n" .. "TR%+0.0fK", obj.level*100/obj.cap,balset,obj.rate,obj.level/1000,obj.target/1000,obj.trim/1000)) if not obj.leak then screen.setColor(16,16,16) end screen.drawText(x,y+rowh*4, "LEAK") end
function onDraw() w=screen.getWidth() h=screen.getHeight()
sh=rowh*5 sw=w-1 y=rowh*5 x=0 drawsub(x,y,sw,sh) compartment(x+colw*11*2,0,devs[1]) compartment(x+colw*11,0,devs[3]) compartment(x,0,devs[5])
compartment(x+colw*11*2,y+rowh*6,devs[2]) compartment(x+colw*11,y+rowh*6,devs[4]) compartment(x,y+rowh*6,devs[6]) end

object.script:
inf=1/0
function gn(n) return input.getNumber(n) end
function sn(n,v) output.setNumber(n,v) end
function gb(n) return input.getBool(n) end
function sb(n,v) output.setBool(n,v) end
-- TV Guided version -- -- Ordnance telemetry protocol (output) -- We overlay the contact age field since I never found it to work anyway -- These fields are optional and the booleans specify whether the piece of ordnance provides them -- Boolean 9: Lock ordinal: If true, Numeric 4 contains the contact ordinal of the locked or targeted contact -- Boolean 10: FOV: If true, Number 8 contains the FOV of the weapon's sensors for drawing a targeting ring -- on the HUD -- Boolean 11 Range. Offer sensor range on Numeric 12 to draw a ring on the radar -- Boolean 12 Velocity on Numeric 20 -- Boolean 13 Compass on Numeric 24
-- Number 4: Ordinal of lock-on contact. In the case of stock missile radar heads, it's always the closest contact -- Number 8: FOV so that it can be displayed on the HUD -- Number 12: Weapon sensor/targeting range in meters -- Number 16: Reserved for ordnance type read from hardpoint and inserted later by MCU -- Number 20: Velocity -- Number 24: Compass -- Number 32: Reserved for radar MCU to track radar display scale/radius in m
-- Protocol (input) -- Numeric 1: Yaw command -- Numeric 2: Unused roll command -- Numeric 3: Pitch -- Numeric 4: Unused vertical command -- Numeric 5: RX freq (TX=RX+1)
-- Numeric 32: Hardpoint #/bus address -- Boolean 1: Launch (applied also to hardpoint) -- Boolean 9: Enable the weapon's sensors (radar etc.) which should use the game's standard radar -- protocol to report contacts on the composite-out. -- Check gb(9) to see whether the pilot is scanning for a target.
function onTick()
local range=inf local nearest=0 local r local present
scan=gb(9)
if not scan then return end
--[[ for i=1,8,1 do present = gb(i) sb(i,present) if present then r=gn(i*4-3) if r < range and r > 100 then -- Assume that anything inside 100m is self-detection range=r nearest=i end end end ]]
for i=1,32,1 do sn(i,gn(i)) end
sb(9,false) -- Notify we will report a target ordinal sb(10,false) -- Notify we will report sensor/radar FOV sb(11,false) -- Notify we will provide sensor range sb(12,true) -- Speed sb(13,true) -- Compass
-- sn(4,nearest) -- sn(8,20) -- Roughly 20 degrees -- sn(12,2000) -- 2km gives about a 20 degree X/Y FOV. Should match the radar head configuration. end
function onDraw() end
